<subSubSection id="C3393AC3FFA8865D9D879978FA86F94A" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="593" pageId="1" pageNumber="591" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B9C6948FFA8865F9D879978FB0AFD16" blockId="1.[151,1436,152,735]" pageId="1" pageNumber="591">
<emphasis id="B957B55AFFA8865F9D879978FEF2FD98" bold="true" box="[199,326,570,593]" pageId="1" pageNumber="591">Discussion.</emphasis>
The generic diagnosis by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB214B9FFA8865F9F249978FC16FD98" author="Grimaldi" box="[612,930,570,593]" pageId="1" pageNumber="591" refString="Grimaldi, D. A. &amp; Cumming, J. M. (1999) Brachyceran Diptera in Cretaceous ambers and Mesozoic diversification of the Eremoneura. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 239, 1 - 124." type="journal article" year="1999">Grimaldi &amp; Cumming (1999)</bibRefCitation>
based on 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB214B9FFA8865F99519978FB04FD98" author="Hennig" box="[1041,1200,570,593]" pageId="1" pageNumber="591" refString="Hennig, W. (1971) Insektenfossilien aus der unteren Kreide. III. Empidiformia (&quot; Microphorinae &quot;) aus der unteren Kreide und aus dem baltischen Bernstein; ein Vertreter der Cyclorrhapha aus der unteren Kreide. Stuttgarter Beitrage zur Naturkunde, 232, 1 - 28." type="journal article" year="1971">Hennig (1971)</bibRefCitation>
, with supplements by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB214B9FFA8865F9DD7991FFEE6FDBD" box="[151,338,604,628]" pageId="1" pageNumber="591" refString="Nel, A., Perrichot, V., Daugeron, C. &amp; Neraudeau, D. (2004) A new Microphorites in the Lower Cretaceous amber of the southwest of France (Diptera: Dolichopodidae, &quot; Microphorinae &quot;). Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France, New Series, 40, 23 - 29." type="journal article">
Nel 
<emphasis id="B957B55AFFA8865F9D87991FFF43FDBD" box="[199,247,604,628]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="591">et al</emphasis>
. (2004)
</bibRefCitation>
, is followed. Our fossil has the typical characters for 
<taxonomicName id="4C2312CBFFA8865F9EE7991EFB8AFDBD" box="[935,1086,604,628]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Microphorites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="591" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B957B55AFFA8865F9EE7991EFB8AFDBD" box="[935,1086,604,628]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="591">Microphorites</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, e.g., antennae located near the middle of anterior margins of the eyes; arista 2-articled; anal margin of wing not making a strong curvature; three radial veins; crossvein r-m in basal fourth of wing; crossvein bm-cu complete; cell dm present; two medial veins and vein CuA1 complete; absence of acanthophorite spines on tergite 10 of the female; female abdomen telescopic.
</paragraph>
