<paragraph id="8B9C6948FFAA865D9D879FC4FDE8FAE1" blockId="3.[151,1436,1157,1667]" pageId="3" pageNumber="593">
Among the fossils currently attributed to the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C2312CBFFAA865D9FBD9FC7FB92FB54" authority="Macquart, 1827" authorityName="Macquart" authorityYear="1827" box="[765,1062,1157,1181]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Microphor" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B957B55AFFAA865D9FBD9FC7FCDBFB54" box="[765,879,1157,1181]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="593">Microphor</emphasis>
Macquart, 1827
</taxonomicName>
, our fossil differs from the poorly known 
<taxonomicName id="4C2312CBFFAA865D9DA99FEAFD16FB09" authority="Handlirsch, 1910" authorityName="Handlirsch" authorityYear="1910" box="[233,674,1192,1216]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Microphor" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="defunctus">
<emphasis id="B957B55AFFAA865D9DA99FEAFE7FFB09" box="[233,459,1192,1216]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="593">Microphor defunctus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFB214B9FFAA865D9C9C9FEBFD2EFB09" author="Handlirsch" box="[476,666,1193,1216]" pageId="3" pageNumber="593" refString="Handlirsch, A. (1910) Canadian Fossil Insects. Insects from the Tertiary lake deposits of the southern interior of British Columbia, collected by Mr. Lawrence M. Lambe, in 1906. Contributions to Canadian Palaeontology, Volume 2. Canada Department of Mines, Geological Survey Branch, Memoir, 12 - P, 93 - 129." type="journal article" year="1910">Handlirsch, 1910</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
in the smaller wings (
<quantity id="4CDBC4ADFFAA865D9EDC9FEBFC4AFB09" box="[924,1022,1193,1216]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.11" pageId="3" pageNumber="593" unit="mm" value="2.11">2.11 mm</quantity>
long instead of 4.0 mm) (
<bibRefCitation id="EFB214B9FFAA865D98659FEBFF64FB2A" author="Handlirsch" pageId="3" pageNumber="593" refString="Handlirsch, A. (1910) Canadian Fossil Insects. Insects from the Tertiary lake deposits of the southern interior of British Columbia, collected by Mr. Lawrence M. Lambe, in 1906. Contributions to Canadian Palaeontology, Volume 2. Canada Department of Mines, Geological Survey Branch, Memoir, 12 - P, 93 - 129." type="journal article" year="1910">Handlirsch 1910</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="4C2312CBFFAA865D9DA69F89FDCAFB2A" authority="Meunier, 1902" authorityName="Meunier" authorityYear="1902" box="[230,638,1227,1251]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Microphor" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eocenica">
<emphasis id="B957B55AFFAA865D9DA69F89FE77FB2A" box="[230,451,1227,1251]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="593">Microphor eocenica</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFB214B9FFAA865D9C959F8EFDCCFB2A" author="Meunier" box="[469,632,1228,1251]" pageId="3" pageNumber="593" refString="Meunier, F. (1902) Etude de quelques Dipteres de l'ambre. Annales de Science Naturelle, Zoologie, Series 8, 16, 395 - 406." type="journal article" year="1902">Meunier, 1902</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
has a short postpedicel and wing length 
<quantity id="4CDBC4ADFFAA865D99129F8EFB0CFB2A" box="[1106,1208,1228,1251]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" pageId="3" pageNumber="593" unit="mm" value="0.75">0.75 mm</quantity>
, unlike in our fossil (
<bibRefCitation id="EFB214B9FFAA865D9DDE9FACFE8EFACC" author="Meunier" box="[158,314,1262,1285]" pageId="3" pageNumber="593" refString="Meunier, F. (1902) Etude de quelques Dipteres de l'ambre. Annales de Science Naturelle, Zoologie, Series 8, 16, 395 - 406." type="journal article" year="1902">Meunier 1902</bibRefCitation>
: 402; 1908). 
<taxonomicName id="4C2312CBFFAA865D9C869FAFFCFCFACC" authority="Meunier, 1908" authorityName="Meunier" authorityYear="1908" box="[454,840,1261,1285]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Microphor" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rusticus">
<emphasis id="B957B55AFFAA865D9C869FAFFD20FACC" box="[454,660,1261,1285]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="593">Microphor rusticus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFB214B9FFAA865D9FE19FACFCF5FACC" author="Meunier" box="[673,833,1262,1285]" pageId="3" pageNumber="593" refString="Meunier, F. (1908) Monographie des Empidae de l'ambre de la Baltique. Annales de Science Naturelle, Zoologie, Series 9, 7, 81 - 135." type="journal article" year="1908">Meunier, 1908</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
has an elongate postpedicel, but not pear-shaped unlike in our fossil (
<bibRefCitation id="EFB214B9FFAA865D9C649E53FDFBFAE1" author="Meunier" box="[292,591,1297,1320]" pageId="3" pageNumber="593" refString="Meunier, F. (1908) Monographie des Empidae de l'ambre de la Baltique. Annales de Science Naturelle, Zoologie, Series 9, 7, 81 - 135." type="journal article" year="1908">Meunier 1908: pl. 6, fig. 12</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9C6948FFAA865D9D879E76FB72FA31" blockId="3.[151,1436,1157,1667]" pageId="3" pageNumber="593">
Within the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C2312CBFFAA865D9CC89E71FDABFA82" box="[392,543,1331,1355]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Microphorites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B957B55AFFAA865D9CC89E71FDABFA82" box="[392,543,1331,1355]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="593">Microphorites</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the new fossil differs from all species except 
<taxonomicName id="4C2312CBFFAA865D99629E76FB02FA82" box="[1058,1206,1332,1355]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Microphorites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="moravicus">
<emphasis id="B957B55AFFAA865D99629E76FB02FA82" box="[1058,1206,1332,1355]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="593">M. moravicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the presence of a pterostigma. It differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C2312CBFFAA865D9C829E14FDE1FAA4" box="[450,597,1366,1389]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Microphorites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="moravicus">
<emphasis id="B957B55AFFAA865D9C829E14FDE1FAA4" box="[450,597,1366,1389]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="593">M. moravicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in few characters, viz. in the shape of the scape and pedicel. In 
<taxonomicName id="4C2312CBFFAA865D98499E14FA28FAA4" box="[1289,1436,1366,1389]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Microphorites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="moravicus">
<emphasis id="B957B55AFFAA865D98499E14FA28FAA4" box="[1289,1436,1366,1389]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="593">M. moravicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the scape and pedicel are longer than broad, whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="4C2312CBFFAA865D9E479E3BFCD8FA59" box="[775,876,1400,1424]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Microphorites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erikai" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B957B55AFFAA865D9E479E3BFCD8FA59" box="[775,876,1400,1424]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="593">M. erikai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2640821FFAA865D9E359E3BFC7AFA59" box="[885,974,1401,1424]" pageId="3" pageNumber="593" rank="species">
<emphasis id="B957B55AFFAA865D9E359E3BFC7AFA59" bold="true" box="[885,974,1401,1424]" pageId="3" pageNumber="593">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
they are broader than long. However, the distinctive shape of the scape and pedicel in 
<taxonomicName id="4C2312CBFFAA865D9F309EDEFCB6FA7A" box="[624,770,1436,1459]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Microphorites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="moravicus">
<emphasis id="B957B55AFFAA865D9F309EDEFCB6FA7A" box="[624,770,1436,1459]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="593">M. moravicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
could be due to taphonomic deformation in amber. The thorax of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2312CBFFAA865D9DF59EFCFEACFA1C" box="[181,280,1469,1493]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Microphorites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erikai">
<emphasis id="B957B55AFFAA865D9DF59EFCFEACFA1C" box="[181,280,1469,1493]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="593">M. erikai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is higher than longer, unlike 
<taxonomicName id="4C2312CBFFAA865D9F179EFCFD5EFA1C" box="[599,746,1470,1493]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Microphorites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="moravicus">
<emphasis id="B957B55AFFAA865D9F179EFCFD5EFA1C" box="[599,746,1470,1493]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="593">M. moravicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The head of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2312CBFFAA865D9EC39EFCFC51FA1C" box="[899,997,1469,1493]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Microphorites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erikai">
<emphasis id="B957B55AFFAA865D9EC39EFCFC51FA1C" box="[899,997,1469,1493]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="593">M. erikai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is larger than that of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2312CBFFAA865D99909EFCFAD7FA1C" box="[1232,1379,1470,1493]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Microphorites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="moravicus">
<emphasis id="B957B55AFFAA865D99909EFCFAD7FA1C" box="[1232,1379,1470,1493]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="593">M. moravicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Our fossil also has long setae at the base of the anal margin of the wing, apparently unlike 
<taxonomicName id="4C2312CBFFAA865D996C9EA3FB0BFA31" box="[1068,1215,1505,1528]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Microphorites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="moravicus">
<emphasis id="B957B55AFFAA865D996C9EA3FB0BFA31" box="[1068,1215,1505,1528]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="593">M. moravicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9C6948FFAA865D9D879D46FA86F94A" blockId="3.[151,1436,1157,1667]" pageId="3" pageNumber="593">
There is some uncertainty concerning the age of the amber in which the 
<typeStatus id="5498D7EAFFAA865D99569D46FBF0F9D2" box="[1046,1092,1540,1563]" pageId="3" pageNumber="593">type</typeStatus>
specimen of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2312CBFFAA865D99A59D46FAC9F9D2" box="[1253,1405,1540,1563]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Microphorites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="moravicus">
<emphasis id="B957B55AFFAA865D99A59D46FAC9F9D2" box="[1253,1405,1540,1563]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="593">M. moravicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is embedded. The sediment from which it was found is Paleogene in age, but the amber itself is similar to some Late Cretaceous ambers (
<bibRefCitation id="EFB214B9FFAA865D9C3E9D0BFDFFF9A9" author="Tkoc" box="[382,587,1608,1632]" pageId="3" pageNumber="593" refString="Tkoc, M., Nel, A. &amp; Prokop, J. (2016) Discovery of a new species of the Cretaceous genus Microphorites Hennig, 1971 (Diptera: Dolichopodidae s. lat.) in Paleogene amber from eastern Moravia (Czech Republic). Insect Systematics &amp; Evolution, 47, 181 - 193." type="journal article" year="2016">
Tkoč 
<emphasis id="B957B55AFFAA865D9C859D0BFE48F9A9" box="[453,508,1608,1632]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="593">et al</emphasis>
. 2016
</bibRefCitation>
). With the present discovery, we can confirm the presence of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C2312CBFFAA865D9DD79D29FE9AF94A" box="[151,302,1643,1667]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Microphorites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B957B55AFFAA865D9DD79D29FE9AF94A" box="[151,302,1643,1667]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="593">Microphorites</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the Paleogene and consequently this taxon is present through the Cretaceous-Cenozoic crisis.
</paragraph>
